    "(2.7) Reconstruct the gradient-order lensing B mode templateStarting from the second line of Eq.",
    "(2.2), we see that the gradient order lensing template can be written as∇ i [Q ± iU](n)∇ i ϕ(n), the gradient of QU maps and the lensing potential are given by∇ϕ = - 1 √ 2 {♯ϕ m + ♭ϕm},(2.8)∇(Q + iU) = - 1 √ 2 {♯(Q + iU) m + ♭(Q + iU)m},(2.9)where we have used the relation of gradient operator defined by [27]:D i [ s f (n)] = - 1 √ 2 {♯ s f (n) m + ♭ s f (n)m},(2.10)where ♯ and ♭ are the ladder operators, D i is the gradient operator, s f (n) is a spin-s function and complex-conjugated vectors m and m have the propertym • m = m • m = 0, m • m = 1,(2.11)Given QU maps and a potential map, our initial step involves decomposing them into harmonic coefficients of E-and B-modes.",
    "We prioritize E-modes due to their significantly higher strength compared to B-modes, thus neglecting any leakage from B-modes to E-modes.",
    "Subsequently, we transfer E-modes into a spin-1 field and a spin-3 field using ladder operators.",
    "Additionally, we transform the potential map into spin-1 and spin--1 fields through the operation as follows:Q 3 + iU 3 = ♯(Q + iU) = ℓm (ℓ + 3)(ℓ -2)E ℓm3 Y ℓm,(2.12)Q 1 + iU 1 = ♭(Q + iU) = - ℓm (ℓ + 2)(ℓ -1)E ℓm1 Y ℓm,(2.13)♯ϕ = ℓm ℓ(ℓ + 1)ϕ ℓm1 Y ℓm,(2.14)♭ϕ = - ℓm ℓ(ℓ + 1)ϕ ℓm-1 Y ℓm,(2.15)where Q represents the real part of a field, and U represents the imaginary part of a field."
